{"success":true,"category":"regional-center","urgency":"high","emotional_state":"stressed","needs_action":true,"tone_level":"adversarial","empathy":"This is urgent — you're in the critical 10-day Aid Paid Pending window. Let's act immediately to protect your son's current services.","clarifying_question":null,"answer":"You have 4 days left to file a Fair Hearing appeal with Aid Paid Pending, which will keep Teddy's full 20 hours of ABA in place during the entire appeal process. This is your most powerful protection right now. Do not wait — file the appeal TODAY or tomorrow at the latest. Regional Center of the East Bay must receive your written appeal request within 10 days of the Notice of Action date to preserve Aid Paid Pending rights.","action_steps":[{"step":1,"action":"Email your Fair Hearing appeal request to Regional Center of the East Bay NOW","who":"Send to both your service coordinator AND RCEB's Fair Hearing department (look for email on the Notice of Action, or call 510-618-6100 to confirm)","timeline":"TODAY — do not wait. You have 4 days left for Aid Paid Pending","script":"Subject: URGENT: Fair Hearing Appeal Request - Aid Paid Pending

I am formally requesting a Fair Hearing to appeal the Notice of Action dated [date] reducing my son Teddy's ABA services from 20 to 10 hours per week. I am exercising my right to Aid Paid Pending under W&I Code §4710.5. I request that Teddy's current 20 hours per week of ABA continue unchanged during the appeal process. This appeal is filed within 10 days of the Notice of Action. Please confirm receipt immediately.

[Your name, Teddy's full name, case number]"},{"step":2,"action":"Follow up with a phone call within 2 hours of sending the email","who":"Call RCEB directly at 510-618-6100, ask for Fair Hearing department","timeline":"Same day as email","script":"I just emailed a Fair Hearing appeal request for my son Teddy [last name], case number [X]. This is time-sensitive — I'm within the 10-day Aid Paid Pending window. Can you confirm you received my email and that Aid Paid Pending is in effect? I need written confirmation that his 20 hours per week will continue during the appeal."},{"step":3,"action":"Send the same appeal request via certified mail with return receipt","who":"Mail to RCEB's physical address (check your Notice of Action for exact address)","timeline":"Tomorrow morning at the latest","script":"Include the exact same written appeal from Step 1. Keep your certified mail receipt and tracking number. This creates an undeniable paper trail."},{"step":4,"action":"Contact Disability Rights California for free legal representation","who":"Call 1-800-776-5746 immediately","timeline":"Within 24 hours","script":"My Regional Center just reduced my son's ABA hours and I filed a Fair Hearing appeal. I need legal help preparing for the hearing. Can you represent us or advise me on how to build my case?"}],"rights_reminder":"You have the absolute legal right to a Fair Hearing (W&I Code §4710.5) and Aid Paid Pending if you appeal within 10 days of the Notice of Action. RC cannot legally reduce Teddy's hours while the appeal is pending if you file in time. This is not optional for them — it is your statutory right.","watch_out":"The 10-day Aid Paid Pending clock is counting down RIGHT NOW. If you miss this deadline, RC can reduce services immediately even while your appeal proceeds. Email AND call AND mail today to cover all bases. Do not assume RC will be lenient with the deadline — protect yourself with multiple forms of proof.","offer_to_draft":"I can draft a comprehensive Fair Hearing appeal letter that explains why Teddy's 20 hours are medically necessary, documents his progress, and cites the specific legal violations in RC's reduction decision. This will be stronger than the basic script above.","draft_type":"appeal_letter","sources":["W&I Code §4710.5 (Fair Hearing rights)","W&I Code §4710.5(a) (Aid Paid Pending - 10-day window)","W&I Code §4646 (IPP as governing document)"]}

{"success":true,"category":"iep","urgency":"high","emotional_state":"stressed","needs_action":true,"tone_level":"assertive","empathy":"That's incredibly frustrating — you're trying to get your child the support they need, and the school keeps pushing it off. This isn't okay, and you have every right to push back.","clarifying_question":"Have you already reached out to the school in writing (email or letter) asking them to confirm a firm meeting date? And do you know why they keep canceling?","answer":"Under IDEA, the school district has strict timelines they must follow — and repeated cancellations can violate your child's right to FAPE. If this is an initial IEP, they had 30 days from the assessment to hold the meeting. If it's an annual review, it's overdue. Either way, three cancellations in two months is a red flag. You need to document this pattern and insist on a firm date in writing. If they continue to delay, you can file a compliance complaint with the California Department of Education — they take timeline violations seriously.","action_steps":[{"step":1,"action":"Send a firm written request for an IEP meeting date","who":"Email your school's Special Education Director or Case Manager","timeline":"Within 24 hours","script":"Subject: Urgent — Request for Confirmed IEP Meeting Date

Dear [Name],

This is my third request for an IEP meeting for teddy. The meetings scheduled on [date 1], [date 2], and [date 3] were all canceled by the school. I am requesting that you provide me with a confirmed meeting date within the next 10 calendar days, along with written confirmation that this meeting will not be rescheduled. Please respond within 48 hours with available dates and times. Thank you."},{"step":2,"action":"If they cancel again or don't respond, escalate to the district Special Education Director","who":"Call AND email the district-level Special Ed Director","timeline":"If no response in 48 hours","script":"I have requested an IEP meeting for my child three times over two months, and the school has canceled each time. Under IDEA, my child has a right to timely IEP meetings. I am formally requesting that the district provide a confirmed meeting date within 5 business days and explain in writing why these meetings have been repeatedly canceled."},{"step":3,"action":"File a compliance complaint if the pattern continues","who":"California Department of Education (CDE)","timeline":"If meeting is not held within 10 days of your written request","script":"Call CDE at (916) 319-0800 and say: 'I need to file a compliance complaint against [school district name] for repeatedly canceling my child's IEP meeting. This has happened three times over two months, and I believe they are violating IDEA timelines.'"}],"rights_reminder":"Under IDEA §300.322 and CA Ed Code §56341, the school must schedule IEP meetings at mutually agreed-upon times and cannot repeatedly cancel without violating your child's right to FAPE. If this is an initial IEP, they had 30 days from assessment completion. If it's an annual review, it's legally overdue after one year. Repeated cancellations are a procedural violation you can report.","watch_out":"Keep a detailed record of every cancellation — dates, who canceled, and the reason given (if any). Save all emails and texts. If they say 'we don't have staff available' or 'we're too busy,' that's not a valid legal reason to deny your child's IEP meeting. The complaint process is stronger when you have clear documentation of the pattern.","offer_to_draft":"I can help you draft a firm email to the school requesting a confirmed IEP meeting date, or escalate to the district if they continue canceling. Would you like me to set that up for you?","draft_type":"iep_email","sources":["IDEA §300.322 (parent participation in IEP meetings)","CA Ed Code §56341 (IEP meeting timelines)","CA Ed Code §56043 (30-day timeline for initial IEP after assessment)"]}
